        <custodhist id="ref19">
            <head>Provenance</head>
            <p>This collection was created by Anna Pollin, Director of the New York University program in Spain and founder of the Institute for Computer Research in the Humanities. She transferred the collection to Professor Bayrd Still of the New York University Department of History in 1982. The documents were later transferred to the New York University Archives.</p>
        </custodhist>
        <bioghist id="ref14">
            <head>History</head>
            <p>The Institute for Computer Research in the Humanities began after Dr. Alice Pollin of the Spanish Department at University College proposed a project that involved creating a computer index of the 
                <emph render="italic">Revista de Filogia Espanola</emph>, a collection of Hispanic literature and linguistics. This project illuminated the potential for merging computer technology with humanities research to advance research and writing techniques. Early proposals for the program included projects that would catalogue literature and literary criticism and develop technology for music analysis. The Institute was officially created in September 1965. It actively promoted computer research in the humanities for over five years. In July 1969 the Institute was shuttered due to lack of funding.</p>
        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent id="ref1">
            <head>Scope and Contents Note</head>
            <p>The collection comprises the Institute's historical papers, including three project proposals, newsletters, conference materials, and clippings.</p>
        </scopecontent>
